Note: ============================================================================
Note: R SEMANTIC ANALYZER
Note: ============================================================================
Note: Semantic analysis for R statistical computing language
Note: Handles R-specific features:
Note: - Data frames and vectors
Note: - Statistical functions and packages
Note: - Environments and scoping
Note: - S3/S4 object systems
Note: - Dynamic typing with type inference
Note: - Package imports (library/require)
Note: - Formula syntax (y ~ x)

Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/hir_nodes.runa" as HirNodes
Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/hir_builder.runa" as HirBuilder

Type called "RSemanticContext":
    current_environment as REnvironment
    parent_context as RSemanticContext
    global_packages as List[String]
    current_function as String
    error_list as List[String]
    warning_list as List[String]
    type_cache as Dictionary[String, RType]
    s3_classes as Dictionary[String, RS3ClassInfo]
    s4_classes as Dictionary[String, RS4ClassInfo]
End Type

Type called "REnvironment":
    variables as Dictionary[String, RVariable]
    functions as Dictionary[String, RFunction]
    parent_env as REnvironment
    name as String
    is_global as Boolean
End Type

Type called "RVariable":
    name as String
    type as RType
    is_constant as Boolean
    scope as String
    first_assignment_line as Integer
    last_access_line as Integer
End Type

Note: Local R AST schema. The semantic analyzer expects an enriched node
Note: type carrying language-specific fields; until v0.0.9.x rewires it to
Note: the generic HIRNode + children traversal, this local type satisfies
Note: the analyzer's field accesses.
Type called "RASTNode":
    node_type as String
    name as Integer
    value as Integer
    line as Integer
    type as Integer
    statements as Integer
    body as Integer
    arguments as Integer
    parameters as Integer
    function_name as Integer
    initializer as Integer
    operator as Integer
    target as Integer
    accessor as Integer
    access_type as Integer
    dataframe as Integer
    package_name as Integer
    is_require as Integer
    interactions as Integer
    predictors as Integer
    response as Integer
    literal_type as Integer
End Type

Type called "RFunction":
    name as String
    parameters as List[RParameter]
    return_type as RType
    is_generic as Boolean
    is_s3_method as Boolean
    is_s4_method as Boolean
    package as String
End Type

Type called "RParameter":
    name as String
    type as RType
    has_default as Boolean
    default_value as String
    is_variadic as Boolean
End Type

Type called "RType":
    base_type as String
    dimensions as List[Integer]
    element_type as RType
    attributes as Dictionary[String, String]
    is_factor as Boolean
    factor_levels as List[String]
    class_name as String
End Type

Type called "RS3ClassInfo":
    class_name as String
    parent_classes as List[String]
    methods as Dictionary[String, RFunction]
    constructor as RFunction
End Type

Type called "RS4ClassInfo":
    class_name as String
    slots as Dictionary[String, RType]
    parent_classes as List[String]
    methods as Dictionary[String, RFunction]
    validity_function as RFunction
End Type

Type called "RSemanticError":
    message as String
    line as Integer
    column as Integer
    severity as String
    error_code as String
End Type

Note: ============================================================================
Note: MAIN SEMANTIC ANALYSIS ENTRY POINT
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "analyze_r_semantics" that takes ast as RASTNode returns RSemanticContext:
    Note: Main entry point for R semantic analysis

    @Reasoning:
    R has unique semantic requirements including dynamic typing, multiple
    object systems (S3/S4), environments for scoping, and statistical
    data types like data frames and factors.
    @End Reasoning

    Let context be create_global_r_context

    Note: Load standard R packages that are always available
    Call load_base_packages with context

    Note: Analyze the AST
    Call analyze_r_node with ast and context

    Note: Perform final validation
    Call validate_r_semantics with context

    Return context
End Process

Process called "create_global_r_context" that takes nothing returns RSemanticContext:
    Note: Create the global semantic context with base R environment

    Let global_env be a value of type REnvironment with
        variables as a dictionary containing nothing,
        functions as a dictionary containing nothing,
        parent_env as null,
        name as ".GlobalEnv",
        is_global as true

    Let context be a value of type RSemanticContext with
        current_environment as global_env,
        parent_context as null,
        global_packages as a list containing "base", "utils", "stats", "graphics", "grDevices", "methods", "datasets",
        current_function as null,
        error_list as a list containing nothing,
        warning_list as a list containing nothing,
        type_cache as a dictionary containing nothing,
        s3_classes as a dictionary containing nothing,
        s4_classes as a dictionary containing nothing

    Return context
End Process

Process called "load_base_packages" that takes ctx as RSemanticContext returns Nothing:
    Note: Load standard R packages and their functions

    @Reasoning:
    R comes with several standard packages that define built-in functions
    and data types. These need to be available in the global environment.
    @End Reasoning

    Note: Load base package functions
    Call load_base_functions with ctx
    Call load_stats_functions with ctx
    Call load_utils_functions with ctx
    Call load_graphics_functions with ctx

    Note: Load standard data types
    Call load_standard_types with ctx
End Process

Process called "load_base_functions" that takes ctx as RSemanticContext returns Nothing:
    Note: Load core R base functions

    Let base_functions be a list containing:
        create_r_function with "c" and create_variadic_numeric_function,
        create_r_function with "length" and create_single_param_int_function,
        create_r_function with "names" and create_single_param_string_vector_function,
        create_r_function with "class" and create_single_param_string_vector_function,
        create_r_function with "str" and create_single_param_void_function,
        create_r_function with "summary" and create_single_param_summary_function,
        create_r_function with "head" and create_head_tail_function,
        create_r_function with "tail" and create_head_tail_function,
        create_r_function with "paste" and create_paste_function,
        create_r_function with "paste0" and create_paste0_function,
        create_r_function with "cat" and create_cat_function,
        create_r_function with "print" and create_print_function,
        create_r_function with "is.null" and create_is_null_function,
        create_r_function with "is.na" and create_is_na_function,
        create_r_function with "is.finite" and create_is_finite_function,
        create_r_function with "as.character" and create_as_character_function,
        create_r_function with "as.numeric" and create_as_numeric_function,
        create_r_function with "as.logical" and create_as_logical_function,
        create_r_function with "as.integer" and create_as_integer_function

    For Each func in base_functions:
        Set ctx.current_environment.functions at key func.name to func
    End For
End Process

Process called "load_stats_functions" that takes ctx as RSemanticContext returns Nothing:
    Note: Load statistical functions from stats package

    Let stats_functions be a list containing:
        create_r_function with "mean" and create_stats_summary_function,
        create_r_function with "median" and create_stats_summary_function,
        create_r_function with "sd" and create_stats_summary_function,
        create_r_function with "var" and create_stats_summary_function,
        create_r_function with "cor" and create_cor_function,
        create_r_function with "lm" and create_lm_function,
        create_r_function with "glm" and create_glm_function,
        create_r_function with "anova" and create_anova_function,
        create_r_function with "t.test" and create_t_test_function,
        create_r_function with "chisq.test" and create_chisq_test_function,
        create_r_function with "rnorm" and create_rnorm_function,
        create_r_function with "runif" and create_runif_function,
        create_r_function with "rbinom" and create_rbinom_function

    For Each func in stats_functions:
        Set func.package to "stats"
        Set ctx.current_environment.functions at key func.name to func
    End For
End Process

Process called "load_utils_functions" that takes ctx as RSemanticContext returns Nothing:
    Note: Load utility functions from utils package

    Let utils_functions be a list containing:
        create_r_function with "read.csv" and create_read_csv_function,
        create_r_function with "write.csv" and create_write_csv_function,
        create_r_function with "read.table" and create_read_table_function,
        create_r_function with "write.table" and create_write_table_function,
        create_r_function with "install.packages" and create_install_packages_function,
        create_r_function with "remove.packages" and create_remove_packages_function,
        create_r_function with "help" and create_help_function,
        create_r_function with "str" and create_str_function

    For Each func in utils_functions:
        Set func.package to "utils"
        Set ctx.current_environment.functions at key func.name to func
    End For
End Process

Process called "load_graphics_functions" that takes ctx as RSemanticContext returns Nothing:
    Note: Load graphics functions

    Let graphics_functions be a list containing:
        create_r_function with "plot" and create_plot_function,
        create_r_function with "hist" and create_hist_function,
        create_r_function with "boxplot" and create_boxplot_function,
        create_r_function with "barplot" and create_barplot_function,
        create_r_function with "pie" and create_pie_function,
        create_r_function with "lines" and create_lines_function,
        create_r_function with "points" and create_points_function,
        create_r_function with "legend" and create_legend_function

    For Each func in graphics_functions:
        Set func.package to "graphics"
        Set ctx.current_environment.functions at key func.name to func
    End For
End Process

Process called "load_standard_types" that takes ctx as RSemanticContext returns Nothing:
    Note: Load standard R data types

    @Reasoning:
    R has unique data types like data.frame, factor, matrix, list, etc.
    These need to be registered in the type system for proper validation.
    @End Reasoning

    Note: Register basic R types
    Set ctx.type_cache at key "logical" to create_logical_type
    Set ctx.type_cache at key "integer" to create_integer_type
    Set ctx.type_cache at key "numeric" to create_numeric_type
    Set ctx.type_cache at key "complex" to create_complex_type
    Set ctx.type_cache at key "character" to create_character_type
    Set ctx.type_cache at key "raw" to create_raw_type

    Note: Register complex R types
    Set ctx.type_cache at key "data.frame" to create_data_frame_type
    Set ctx.type_cache at key "list" to create_list_type
    Set ctx.type_cache at key "matrix" to create_matrix_type
    Set ctx.type_cache at key "array" to create_array_type
    Set ctx.type_cache at key "factor" to create_factor_type
    Set ctx.type_cache at key "function" to create_function_type

    Note: Register S3 classes
    Call register_s3_classes with ctx

    Note: Register S4 classes
    Call register_s4_classes with ctx
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: AST NODE ANALYSIS
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "analyze_r_node" that takes node as RASTNode, ctx as RSemanticContext returns Nothing:
    Note: Analyze any R AST node based on its type

    Match node.node_type:
        When "Program":
            Call analyze_r_program with node and ctx
        When "FunctionDeclaration":
            Call analyze_r_function_declaration with node and ctx
        When "VariableDeclaration":
            Call analyze_r_variable_declaration with node and ctx
        When "Assignment":
            Call analyze_r_assignment with node and ctx
        When "FunctionCall":
            Call analyze_r_function_call with node and ctx
        When "FormulaExpression":
            Call analyze_r_formula with node and ctx
        When "LibraryCall":
            Call analyze_r_library_call with node and ctx
        When "DataFrameAccess":
            Call analyze_r_dataframe_access with node and ctx
        When "VectorOperation":
            Call analyze_r_vector_operation with node and ctx
        When "IfStatement":
            Call analyze_r_if_statement with node and ctx
        When "ForLoop":
            Call analyze_r_for_loop with node and ctx
        When "WhileLoop":
            Call analyze_r_while_loop with node and ctx
        Otherwise:
            Call analyze_generic_node with node and ctx
    End Match
End Process

Process called "analyze_r_program" that takes node as RASTNode, ctx as RSemanticContext returns Nothing:
    Note: Analyze R program (top-level statements)

    For Each statement in node.statements:
        Call analyze_r_node with statement and ctx
    End For
End Process

Process called "analyze_r_function_declaration" that takes node as RASTNode, ctx as RSemanticContext returns Nothing:
    Note: Analyze R function declaration

    @Reasoning:
    R functions can be assigned to variables and have complex parameter
    handling including default values, variadic arguments (...), and
    lazy evaluation.
    @End Reasoning

    Let func_name be node.name
    Let parameters be node.parameters
    Let body be node.body

    Note: Create function environment
    Let func_env be create_function_environment with ctx.current_environment and func_name

    Note: Analyze parameters
    Let r_params be a list containing nothing
    For Each param as RASTNode in parameters:
        Let r_param be analyze_r_parameter with param and ctx of type RParameter
        Add r_param to end of r_params

        Note: Add parameter to function environment
        Let param_var be a value of type RVariable with
            name as param.name,
            type as r_param.type,
            is_constant as false,
            scope as func_name,
            first_assignment_line as param.line,
            last_access_line as param.line

        Set func_env.variables at key param.name to param_var
    End For

    Note: Create function object
    Let r_function be a value of type RFunction with
        name as func_name,
        parameters as r_params,
        return_type as create_any_type,
        is_generic as false,
        is_s3_method as check_is_s3_method with func_name,
        is_s4_method as check_is_s4_method with func_name,
        package as null

    Note: Set function context and analyze body
    Let old_env be ctx.current_environment
    Let old_func be ctx.current_function
    Set ctx.current_environment to func_env
    Set ctx.current_function to func_name

    Call analyze_r_node with body and ctx

    Note: Restore context
    Set ctx.current_environment to old_env
    Set ctx.current_function to old_func

    Note: Register function in environment
    Set ctx.current_environment.functions at key func_name to r_function
End Process

Process called "analyze_r_variable_declaration" that takes node as RASTNode, ctx as RSemanticContext returns Nothing:
    Note: Analyze R variable declaration

    Let var_name be node.name
    Let var_type be node.node_type
    Let initializer be node.initializer

    Note: Check if variable already exists
    If ctx.current_environment.variables contains key var_name:
        Let warning be "Variable '" joined with var_name joined with "' already exists and will be overwritten"
        Add warning to end of ctx.warning_list
    End If

    Note: Infer type from initializer if present
    Let inferred_type be create_any_type
    If initializer is not equal to 0:
        Set inferred_type to infer_r_expression_type with initializer and ctx
        Call analyze_r_node with initializer and ctx
    End If

    Note: Create variable
    Let r_variable be a value of type RVariable with
        name as var_name,
        type as inferred_type,
        is_constant as false,
        scope as ctx.current_environment.name,
        first_assignment_line as node.line,
        last_access_line as node.line

    Set ctx.current_environment.variables at key var_name to r_variable
End Process

Process called "analyze_r_assignment" that takes node as RASTNode, ctx as RSemanticContext returns Nothing:
    Note: Analyze R assignment operations

    @Reasoning:
    R supports multiple assignment operators: <-, =, ->, <<-, and ->>
    Each has different semantics for scope and evaluation.
    @End Reasoning

    Let target be node.target
    Let value be node.value
    Let operator be node.operator

    Note: Analyze value expression first
    Call analyze_r_node with value and ctx
    Let value_type be infer_r_expression_type with value and ctx

    Note: Handle different assignment types
    Match operator:
        When "<-":
            Call analyze_left_assignment with target and value_type and ctx
        When "=":
            Call analyze_equal_assignment with target and value_type and ctx
        When "->":
            Call analyze_right_assignment with target and value_type and ctx
        When "<<-":
            Call analyze_global_left_assignment with target and value_type and ctx
        When "->>":
            Call analyze_global_right_assignment with target and value_type and ctx
        Otherwise:
            Let error be "Unknown assignment operator: " joined with operator
            Add error to end of ctx.error_list
    End Match
End Process

Process called "analyze_r_function_call" that takes node as RASTNode, ctx as RSemanticContext returns Nothing:
    Note: Analyze R function call

    Let func_name be node.function_name
    Let arguments be node.arguments

    Note: Check if function exists
    Let r_function be lookup_r_function with func_name and ctx
    If r_function is equal to 0:
        Note: Check for S3 method dispatch
        Let s3_method be check_s3_method_dispatch with func_name and arguments and ctx of type RFunction
        If s3_method is not equal to 0:
            Set r_function to s3_method
        End If
    End If

    If r_function is equal to 0:
        Let error be "Function '" joined with func_name joined with "' not found"
        Add error to end of ctx.error_list
        Return
    End If

    Note: Analyze arguments
    For Each arg in arguments:
        Call analyze_r_node with arg and ctx
    End For

    Note: Check argument compatibility
    Call validate_r_function_arguments with r_function and arguments and ctx
End Process

Process called "analyze_r_formula" that takes node as RASTNode, ctx as RSemanticContext returns Nothing:
    Note: Analyze R formula expressions (y ~ x)

    @Reasoning:
    R formulas are special expressions used in statistical modeling.
    They have specific syntax and semantic rules for variable references.
    @End Reasoning

    Let response be node.response
    Let predictors be node.predictors
    Let interactions be node.interactions

    Note: Analyze response variable
    If response is not equal to 0:
        Call analyze_r_node with response and ctx
        Call validate_formula_variable with response and ctx
    End If

    Note: Analyze predictor variables
    For Each predictor in predictors:
        Call analyze_r_node with predictor and ctx
        Call validate_formula_variable with predictor and ctx
    End For

    Note: Analyze interactions
    For Each interaction in interactions:
        Call analyze_r_interaction with interaction and ctx
    End For
End Process

Process called "analyze_r_library_call" that takes node as RASTNode, ctx as RSemanticContext returns Nothing:
    Note: Analyze library/require calls

    Let package_name be node.package_name
    Let is_require be node.is_require

    Note: Check if package is already loaded
    If ctx.global_packages contains package_name:
        If not is_require:
            Let warning be "Package '" joined with package_name joined with "' already loaded"
            Add warning to end of ctx.warning_list
        End If
        Return
    End If

    Note: Load package functions and types
    Call load_package_definitions with package_name and ctx

    Note: Add to loaded packages
    Add package_name to end of ctx.global_packages
End Process

Process called "analyze_r_dataframe_access" that takes node as RASTNode, ctx as RSemanticContext returns Nothing:
    Note: Analyze data frame access operations (df$col, df[row, col])

    Let dataframe be node.dataframe
    Let accessor be node.accessor
    Let access_type be node.access_type

    Note: Analyze dataframe expression
    Call analyze_r_node with dataframe and ctx
    Let df_type be infer_r_expression_type with dataframe and ctx

    Note: Validate it's actually a data frame
    If df_type.base_type is not equal to "data.frame":
        Let error be "Attempting data frame access on non-data.frame object"
        Add error to end of ctx.error_list
        Return
    End If

    Note: Analyze accessor based on type
    Match access_type:
        When "column":
            Call analyze_column_access with accessor and df_type and ctx
        When "row":
            Call analyze_row_access with accessor and df_type and ctx
        When "subset":
            Call analyze_subset_access with accessor and df_type and ctx
        Otherwise:
            Set error to "Unknown data frame access type: " joined with access_type
            Add error to end of ctx.error_list
    End Match
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: TYPE INFERENCE AND VALIDATION
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "infer_r_expression_type" that takes expr as RASTNode, ctx as RSemanticContext returns RType:
    Note: Infer the type of an R expression

    @Reasoning:
    R is dynamically typed but we can infer types for better error checking
    and optimization. This handles R's unique type system including vectors,
    factors, and data frames.
    @End Reasoning

    Match expr.type:
        When "Literal":
            Return infer_literal_type with expr
        When "Identifier":
            Return infer_identifier_type with expr and ctx
        When "FunctionCall":
            Return infer_function_call_type with expr and ctx
        When "VectorConstruction":
            Return infer_vector_type with expr and ctx
        When "DataFrameConstruction":
            Return infer_data_frame_type with expr and ctx
        When "BinaryOperation":
            Return infer_binary_operation_type with expr and ctx
        When "UnaryOperation":
            Return infer_unary_operation_type with expr and ctx
        When "FormulaExpression":
            Return create_formula_type
        Otherwise:
            Return create_any_type
    End Match
End Process

Process called "infer_literal_type" that takes expr as RASTNode returns RType:
    Note: Infer type from literal values

    Let value be expr.value
    Let literal_type be expr.literal_type

    Match literal_type:
        When "integer":
            Return create_integer_type
        When "numeric":
            Return create_numeric_type
        When "character":
            Return create_character_type
        When "logical":
            Return create_logical_type
        When "complex":
            Return create_complex_type
        When "raw":
            Return create_raw_type
        Otherwise:
            Return create_any_type
    End Match
End Process

Process called "infer_identifier_type" that takes expr as RASTNode, ctx as RSemanticContext returns RType:
    Note: Infer type from variable reference

    Let var_name be expr.name

    Note: Look up variable in current environment
    Let variable be lookup_r_variable with var_name and ctx
    If variable is not equal to 0:
        Set variable.last_access_line to expr.line
        Return variable.type
    End If

    Note: Check if it's a function
    Let function be lookup_r_function with var_name and ctx
    If function is not equal to 0:
        Return create_function_type
    End If

    Note: Unknown identifier - could be created dynamically
    Let warning be "Unknown identifier: " joined with var_name
    Add warning to end of ctx.warning_list
    Return create_any_type
End Process

Process called "infer_function_call_type" that takes expr as RASTNode, ctx as RSemanticContext returns RType:
    Note: Infer return type from function call

    Let func_name be expr.function_name
    Let r_function be lookup_r_function with func_name and ctx

    If r_function is not equal to 0:
        Return r_function.return_type
    End If

    Note: Try S3 method dispatch
    Let s3_method be check_s3_method_dispatch with func_name and expr.arguments and ctx of type RFunction
    If s3_method is not equal to 0:
        Return s3_method.return_type
    End If

    Note: Unknown function
    Return create_any_type
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: HELPER FUNCTIONS
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "lookup_r_variable" that takes name as String, ctx as RSemanticContext returns RVariable:
    Note: Look up variable in environment chain

    Let current_env be ctx.current_environment
    While current_env is not equal to 0:
        If current_env.variables contains key name:
            Return current_env.variables at key name
        End If
        Set current_env to current_env.parent_env
    End While

    Return null
End Process

Process called "lookup_r_function" that takes name as String, ctx as RSemanticContext returns RFunction:
    Note: Look up function in environment chain

    Let current_env be ctx.current_environment
    While current_env is not equal to 0:
        If current_env.functions contains key name:
            Return current_env.functions at key name
        End If
        Set current_env to current_env.parent_env
    End While

    Return null
End Process

Process called "create_function_environment" that takes parent as REnvironment, func_name as String returns REnvironment:
    Note: Create new environment for function scope

    Return a value of type REnvironment with
        variables as a dictionary containing nothing,
        functions as a dictionary containing nothing,
        parent_env as parent,
        name as func_name,
        is_global as false
End Process

Process called "validate_r_semantics" that takes ctx as RSemanticContext returns Nothing:
    Note: Perform final semantic validation

    @Reasoning:
    Final validation checks for issues that can only be detected after
    the full AST has been analyzed, such as undefined variables used
    in formulas or missing required packages.
    @End Reasoning

    Call validate_variable_usage with ctx
    Call validate_function_usage with ctx
    Call validate_package_dependencies with ctx
    Call validate_s3_methods with ctx
    Call validate_s4_methods with ctx
End Process

Process called "validate_variable_usage" that takes ctx as RSemanticContext returns Nothing:
    Note: Validate all variables were properly used

    Note: This  check for unused variables, uninitialized usage, etc.
    Note: Implementation depends on tracking variable access patterns
End Process

Process called "validate_function_usage" that takes ctx as RSemanticContext returns Nothing:
    Note: Validate function calls are correct

    Note: This  check argument counts, types, etc.
    Note: Implementation depends on detailed function signature tracking
End Process

Process called "validate_package_dependencies" that takes ctx as RSemanticContext returns Nothing:
    Note: Validate required packages are loaded

    Note: Check if functions from unloaded packages are being used
End Process

Process called "validate_s3_methods" that takes ctx as RSemanticContext returns Nothing:
    Note: Validate S3 method definitions and usage

    Note: Check S3 generic/method consistency
End Process

Process called "validate_s4_methods" that takes ctx as RSemanticContext returns Nothing:
    Note: Validate S4 method definitions and usage

    Note: Check S4 class definitions and method signatures
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: TYPE CREATION HELPERS
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "create_logical_type" that takes nothing returns RType:
    Return a value of type RType with
        base_type as "logical",
        dimensions as null,
        element_type as null,
        attributes as a dictionary containing nothing,
        is_factor as false,
        factor_levels as null,
        class_name as null
End Process

Process called "create_integer_type" that takes nothing returns RType:
    Return a value of type RType with
        base_type as "integer",
        dimensions as null,
        element_type as null,
        attributes as a dictionary containing nothing,
        is_factor as false,
        factor_levels as null,
        class_name as null
End Process

